02:24:18,328 --> 02:24:22,331
A great process is having involvement, exchanging of ideas.

1664
02:24:22,931 --> 02:24:24,012
That's a great process.

1665
02:24:24,412 --> 02:24:34,899
Even the school department, after some of the deliberation, came back and added things to the school budget based on recommendations by members of the school committee.

1666
02:24:35,560 --> 02:24:36,881
Did that happen with this body?

1667
02:24:37,641 --> 02:24:40,143
Did anyone come and say, Hey, I know you offered this suggestion.

1668
02:24:40,463 --> 02:24:42,284
Maybe we can't do this, but maybe we could do this.

1669
02:24:43,145 --> 02:24:44,206
Nothing at all.

1670
02:24:45,086 --> 02:24:45,647
Nothing at all.

1671
02:24:45,867 --> 02:24:47,928
And I'm only speaking, maybe it happened to other members.

1672
02:24:48,189 --> 02:24:49,089
It didn't happen with me.

1673
02:24:49,529 --> 02:24:59,316
So I'd like to go through a few of the lowlights that I believe should have been included in this budget items that this council has worked on over the years.

1674
02:24:59,937 --> 02:25:04,200
And we're going to lose progress because of the lack of funding on some of these items.

1675
02:25:04,888 --> 02:25:11,551
And I'm not proud to say that, but it's going to happen and I'm going to lay out in detail and it's going to take some time, Mr. President.

1676
02:25:11,991 --> 02:25:18,634
So, uh, grab your comfy seat and sit back because this is important.

1677
02:25:19,814 --> 02:25:26,477
You know, it's one thing to mention it at a committee, the whole meeting in front of, uh, you know, some administrators.

1678
02:25:26,877 --> 02:25:30,338
And it's another thing to let the general public know what's going on in this community.

1679
02:25:31,839 --> 02:25:32,039
You know,

1680
02:25:32,799 --> 02:25:39,602
For the past two years, this council initiated a line item in the budget.

1681
02:25:40,182 --> 02:25:45,604
We were the ones that initiated a $15,000 line item in the budget for the arts.

1682
02:25:47,145 --> 02:25:48,706
That was monumental in this community.

1683
02:25:48,726 --> 02:25:53,328
It's never been done before to recognize method arts in this community.

1684
02:25:53,908 --> 02:25:55,208
And that was done two years ago.

1685
02:25:56,229 --> 02:25:58,710
And we went to the art community, and we said, you know what?

1686
02:25:59,250 --> 02:26:01,051
This is not going to just be a gravy train.

1687
02:26:01,881 --> 02:26:06,903
If you want additional funding in the budget, you're going to have to prove to us that it's worthy of the funding.

1688
02:26:07,143 --> 02:26:08,924
You're going to have to show us community outreach.

1689
02:26:09,204 --> 02:26:12,985
You're going to have to show us what programming was done with this money.

1690
02:26:14,206 --> 02:26:22,349
And sure enough, the next year came about last year, and this council voted to add another $15,000, bringing it up to $30,000.

1691
02:26:23,329 --> 02:26:31,192
Based on the input we received from the Method Arts Council, Mackie, and all the other artists group in this community that are involved,

1692
02:26:31,547 --> 02:26:40,629
and putting so many good programs like the West Bedford Open Studios, Circle the Square, and the list goes on and on.

1693
02:26:40,649 --> 02:26:48,832
You know, this year, Mr. President, I offered to continue the momentum we had, asking for another $15,000.

1694
02:26:51,481 --> 02:26:57,027
Now it wasn't just to throw $15,000 at a group of artists in the community to please them.

1695
02:26:57,628 --> 02:27:12,404
It was because they've shown us over years that they've been able to take this money and use it in outreach, in reaching out to the community, in setting up programs that impact thousands of Method residents, putting a face in this community.

1696
02:27:12,868 --> 02:27:15,009
that was missed for so many years.

1697
02:27:15,690 --> 02:27:23,474
And I want to go through some of the highlights that were presented to me by the arts community after I offered this.

1698
02:27:24,655 --> 02:27:33,160
And I think it's telling, Mr. President, that some of the facts and figures that they presented us, that the money in the budget they like.

1699
02:27:34,110 --> 02:27:40,075
The money in the budget does not fully fund what they're trying to do, does not even come remotely close.

1700
02:27:40,456 --> 02:27:48,523
And without the money in the budget, there is no art program for all intents and purposes, because the state has been cutting the arts, as we all know, year after year.

1701
02:27:49,083 --> 02:27:53,467
So for 2016, the Method Arts Council gave out $45,300 to 62 projects and field trips in this community.

1702
02:27:59,679 --> 02:28:04,564
This represents an increase of $15,000 over 2015.

1703
02:28:05,465 --> 02:28:14,773
Due to greater funding provided by the city of Method, which is this city council, more projects were funded and an average grant amount increased by 35%.

1704
02:28:14,813 --> 02:28:23,542
So we were able to increase the grants that we provide to these different groups in the community, an additional 35% to do what they do.

1705
02:28:25,444 --> 02:28:28,548
We were also able to fund 11 of these proposals at 100%.

1706
02:28:30,405 --> 02:28:44,611
The total amount requested by the community for 2016 was $93,321, which means that we were unable to meet even 50% of the demand despite our increased budget.

1707
02:28:45,351 --> 02:28:56,856
So even with the increases we made the headway over the last two years, according to the numbers from the Method Arts Council, we were only able to meet less than 50% of what was asked for.

1708
02:28:57,596 --> 02:29:00,617
Our available budget fell short of the total request by $48,000.

1709
02:29:01,557 --> 02:29:07,279
An increased effort to attract new applicants and projects started to be seen in 2016.

1710
02:29:07,339 --> 02:29:14,141
The greater visibility is due to the contribution of outreach and the City of Meffitt's investment.

1711
02:29:14,861 --> 02:29:25,444
The Meffitt Arts Council was also selected, as this council knows, as the 2016 Cultural Council of the Year by the state, just the third council ever chosen for this honor.

1712
02:29:26,024 --> 02:29:35,327
The citation specifically pointed to, among other things, our new level of partnership with the City of Meffitt, our regional leadership and public support for the arts.

1713
02:29:36,447 --> 02:29:44,870
Then it also goes on to say, most of the city's allocations to the Meffitt Arts Council has gone to community grant programs.

1714
02:29:45,370 --> 02:29:46,890
Some of the highlights in 2016, many of which we funded.

1715
02:29:50,092 --> 02:29:51,213
with the budget request.

1716
02:29:52,013 --> 02:29:57,077
A second year of highly successful multimedia cultural exchange at the Senior Center.

1717
02:29:57,698 --> 02:30:03,121
This project caught the attention of the Mass Cultural Council, which was asked to nominate for an award.

1718
02:30:03,542 --> 02:30:06,704
Unfortunately, we did not win, but we were nominated for an award.

1719
02:30:07,445 --> 02:30:17,632
An innovative touch-guided quilt and sewing program for the blind and visually impaired, which is being piloted at the Senior Center with the intention to expand it to other communities.

1720
02:30:18,404 --> 02:30:21,646
Stipends for musicians to play at the Methodist Farmer's Market.

1721
02:30:22,587 --> 02:30:24,589
Artists shouldn't work for free, and they're right.

1722
02:30:24,629 --> 02:30:30,073
If you go down to the Farmer's Market, there's music playing all the time, and it's an upbeat environment.

1723
02:30:31,494 --> 02:30:41,221
Terrific new program at Chevalier Theater, including the onstage series that brings in new kids, kinds of brands, and new audiences to the venue.

1724
02:30:41,621 --> 02:30:46,885
A collaboration between the Monkey House Dance Company and the Boys and Girls Club to introduce choreography,

1725
02:30:47,268 --> 02:30:48,469
and movement to young kids.

1726
02:30:49,149 --> 02:30:54,793
The Meffitt Calling Program, pairing prominent songwriters with aspiring musicians from Meffitt High School.

1727
02:30:55,554 --> 02:31:04,640
We are artistically going to paint our crosswalks, which we'll use art to design and increase pedestrian safety and beautification on our streets.

1728
02:31:05,141 --> 02:31:11,465
These are the things that were done in 2016 by the mayor funding, and I do say mayor funding, in $162 million budget, with the $30,000 budget that we implemented

1729
02:31:17,370 --> 02:31:18,951
by this council back some two years ago.

1730
02:31:19,431 --> 02:31:21,232
So we were looking to increase it to 45.

1731
02:31:21,653 --> 02:31:24,014
The mayor turned that down, unfortunately.

1732
02:31:26,556 --> 02:31:27,656
Chevalier Auditorium.

1733
02:31:28,437 --> 02:31:33,079
You know, we have the budget for Chevalier Auditorium.

1734
02:31:33,700 --> 02:31:36,902
And yes, there was a building custodian put in the budget for $24,749.

1735
02:31:36,962 --> 02:31:38,503
That brings the total budget up to $91,749.

1736
02:31:46,459 --> 02:31:52,904
There is not any money, I shouldn't say that, there is very little money for building improvements.

1737
02:31:53,224 --> 02:31:55,606
There's building repairs, but building improvements.

1738
02:31:56,107 --> 02:32:04,213
I talked to members of the Chevalier Commission, I talked to members of the Friends of Chevalier, and they were all interested.

1739
02:32:04,760 --> 02:32:16,464
in presenting a marquee on the front of Chevalier, to give it a face, to give it a presence, to let people know that it exists, even people in this community to let it know it exists.

1740
02:32:17,364 --> 02:32:27,628
For $20,000 to $30,000, I don't know if you remember about a year ago, there was a movie, a motion picture that was being filmed in the city, and they put an old marquee up on the Chevalier Theater.

1741
02:32:28,461 --> 02:32:33,523
And I kept the picture of it because, really, it put a face on that building that was never seen before.

1742
02:32:33,783 --> 02:32:38,224
There was neon on the sign and so forth, and it attracted you to the building.

1743
02:32:39,084 --> 02:32:42,926
I asked in the budget this year for a $50,000 appropriation.

1744
02:32:43,226 --> 02:32:46,287
Let's not forget, this is a city-owned building.

1745
02:32:47,587 --> 02:32:50,608
This doesn't belong to Joe Smith, Paul Jones.

1746
02:32:50,908 --> 02:32:56,070
This is a city-owned building that the city has lacked to support over the years.

1747
02:32:57,145 --> 02:33:01,850
They'll be the first to say, every elected official, that's the economic engine in the city.

1748
02:33:02,410 --> 02:33:06,154
I heard it over and over again at the debates from the mayor, from the council.

1749
02:33:06,574 --> 02:33:07,916
That's the economic engine.

1750
02:33:08,316 --> 02:33:12,741
And then when it comes time for the budget, the economic engine is running on air.

1751
02:33:13,361 --> 02:33:13,862
Let me tell you.

1752
02:33:15,590 --> 02:33:23,696
We're not like Lowell that puts money into funding their public auditorium and puts money into bringing in entertainers.

1753
02:33:24,157 --> 02:33:27,279
You realize how expensive it is to bring in a top name entertainer?

1754
02:33:28,420 --> 02:33:32,643
You might be talking 40 or 50 or 60,000 as a retainer.

1755
02:33:34,665 --> 02:33:36,166
Chevalier doesn't have that money.

1756
02:33:37,348 --> 02:33:39,828
We have to be committed to that particular building.

1757
02:33:40,529 --> 02:33:48,030
And yes, there's been improvements made, but we're falling short of the mark when it comes to taking that building to the next level.

1758
02:33:49,290 --> 02:33:55,531
And I'm very disappointed that the mayor refused to add a line item for building improvements in Chevalier.

1759
02:33:55,971 --> 02:33:58,192
That's an 1,800 seat theater.

1760
02:33:58,532 --> 02:34:02,292
It's the sixth largest theater in the Boston metropolitan area.

1761
02:34:03,133 --> 02:34:03,853
Sixth largest.

1762
02:34:04,233 --> 02:34:05,753
We have it right in our community.

1763
02:34:06,511 --> 02:34:09,572
It's all volunteer civic commission that oversees it.

1764
02:34:10,512 --> 02:34:19,454
And the city, in their wisdom, funds it for $91,000, which includes a $24,000 building custodian, which is needed.

1765
02:34:20,954 --> 02:34:22,874
But that's not what's needed, Mr. President.

1766
02:34:23,775 --> 02:34:29,056
If you want to look at another city-owned building that this city neglected, just take a look at Brooks Estates.

1767
02:34:30,776 --> 02:34:32,216
Just take a ride up to Brooks Estates.

1768
02:34:33,757 --> 02:34:35,517
Actually, you're better off walking, because the road

1769
02:34:35,873 --> 02:34:36,834
is not adequate enough.

1770
02:34:36,894 --> 02:34:39,356
It's really not safe toe drive up there.

1771
02:34:40,277 --> 02:34:48,483
But that's another city old building that this community neglected for years, depending on volunteers to raise the money, and it's just not happening.

1772
02:34:52,146 --> 02:34:58,852
My next one, Mr President, we heard from Fire Chief Gilberti, and I'm glad Councilor Penta's here.

1773
02:34:59,357 --> 02:35:08,259
because Council of Penta over the last several years push to have the feedback from the administrators involved in our process.

1774
02:35:08,699 --> 02:35:12,380
For years we met with the administrators and we never received their wish list.

1775
02:35:12,680 --> 02:35:15,580
And it was Council of Penta that said, we need to know your wish list.

1776
02:35:15,881 --> 02:35:27,363
Even if it doesn't get implemented, as a council, we need to know what your priorities are and what you think is necessary for DPW, what's necessary for the schools, what's necessary for police and fire.

1777
02:35:29,867 --> 02:35:31,108
We heard from Chief Gilberti.

1778
02:35:31,708 --> 02:35:36,231
He's concerned about the internal fire alarms within our fire stations.

1779
02:35:37,812 --> 02:35:42,194
Now these aren't the fire alarms that communicate back and forth, although those are outdated.

1780
02:35:42,894 --> 02:35:49,518
These are the internal alarms like you or I would have in our home, a smoke detector, a hard wire detector.

1781
02:35:50,419 --> 02:35:54,401
Many of them are 30 and 40 years old, according to Chief Gilberti.

1782
02:35:56,102 --> 02:35:57,483
God forbid something were to happen

1783
02:35:58,372 --> 02:35:59,353
in one of these buildings.

1784
02:36:00,193 --> 02:36:06,177
And we knew that our fire station alarms are inadequate within each station.

1785
02:36:07,097 --> 02:36:12,601
That's a major concern that should be addressed, and it's not addressed in this particular budget.

1786
02:36:14,142 --> 02:36:15,843
You know, we heard from Police Chief Sacco.

1787
02:36:16,823 --> 02:36:22,107
He requested six unmarked cars and six marked cars in the budget.

1788
02:36:24,688 --> 02:36:25,749
Denied by the mayor.

1789
02:36:26,902 --> 02:36:31,607
Now that may be part of some capital improvement plan that we have yet to see.

1790
02:36:32,088 --> 02:36:34,230
We have yet to hear when it's going to come out.

1791
02:36:34,450 --> 02:36:35,311
We don't know what's in it.

1792
02:36:35,651 --> 02:36:36,592
That may be part of it.

1793
02:36:38,054 --> 02:36:38,875
But in my opinion,

1794
02:36:39,570 --> 02:36:47,655
As we've been stating for years, this council, there should be at least two to three cars in each year's budget, at a minimum.

1795
02:36:48,035 --> 02:36:52,938
These cars are running 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and they have multiple drivers.

1796
02:36:53,219 --> 02:36:54,099
Think about your car.

1797
02:36:54,820 --> 02:36:58,002
You get out of it after work, it sits in the driveway for 12 hours.

1798
02:36:58,842 --> 02:37:06,447
Someone doesn't get in it and drive it for another 12 hours and drive it a different way than you're driving, which is harmful to a car.

1799
02:37:07,604 --> 02:37:11,787
These cars that we have right now are experiencing transmission problems.

1800
02:37:13,308 --> 02:37:16,730
These cars we have right now are inadequate in the community.

1801
02:37:16,750 --> 02:37:19,692
They spend much of their time being serviced.

1802
02:37:21,933 --> 02:37:27,517
You know, you can't provide public, public safety is probably the most important issue that we provide for.

1803
02:37:28,157 --> 02:37:31,720
You can't provide public safety with inadequate equipment.

1804
02:37:32,940 --> 02:37:35,042
We already know the police department should be condemned.

1805
02:37:36,445 --> 02:37:37,947
We determined that years ago.

1806
02:37:38,667 --> 02:37:45,513
And now we have vehicles that the mayor's allowing our brave men and women drive around in that are inadequate.

1807
02:37:46,533 --> 02:37:47,234
They really are.

1808
02:37:48,355 --> 02:37:49,616
And it's not part of the budget.

1809
02:37:51,137 --> 02:37:52,518
We also heard from the chief.

1810
02:37:53,319 --> 02:38:02,346
He said, I'd like to have some civilians, roughly four civilians, to do some crime analysis, to do some IT work in the department.

1811
02:38:03,970 --> 02:38:14,715
That could go a long way to advising people what's going on in this community, having some crime analysis available, crime analysis on the website.

1812
02:38:14,735 --> 02:38:23,379
You know, I attended the West Method, as well as Councilor Caviello, the West Method Crime Watch that they had several weeks back.

1813
02:38:24,239 --> 02:38:25,940
And over and over again, we heard

1814
02:38:26,538 --> 02:38:29,921
We would like a place where we can go and see crime statistics.

1815
02:38:30,221 --> 02:38:34,685
We'd like to know what's not only happening in our neighborhood, but happening in other sections of the community.

1816
02:38:35,085 --> 02:38:37,487
That currently doesn't exist in this community.

1817
02:38:38,088 --> 02:38:43,352
The chief asked for that, which to me is a very reasonable request, and that was denied.

1818
02:38:43,712 --> 02:38:47,435
The vehicles and the civilian positions was denied in the budget.

1819
02:38:48,756 --> 02:38:51,959
You know, a small request that was something that I asked for.

1820
02:38:51,979 --> 02:38:55,562
You know, I was approached by one of the poll workers.

1821
02:38:56,213 --> 02:38:57,273
months and months back.

1822
02:38:57,934 --> 02:39:02,595
And she said, you realize when we're at a poll, we could be there from 12 to 14 hours.

1823
02:39:04,015 --> 02:39:08,497
She said, nothing against the police, but they're there and they get a box lunch.

1824
02:39:10,177 --> 02:39:17,259
The workers that are checking people in, checking people out, working their 12 to 14 hours, get nothing, absolutely nothing.

1825
02:39:17,599 --> 02:39:22,921
In a busy state and federal election, many of them can't even leave in a busy election.

1826
02:39:24,585 --> 02:39:27,167
So we're asking them to sit in there for 12 to 14 hours.

1827
02:39:27,567 --> 02:39:33,751
I put in a request to add $3,000 to the budget.

1828
02:39:33,771 --> 02:39:38,915
A line item 5780 for $3,000 to pay for some lunches, box lunches.

1829
02:39:39,335 --> 02:39:43,038
And we could do it, the city clerk could do it any way he like.

1830
02:39:43,078 --> 02:39:48,842
He could provide pizza, box lunches, he can give people a stipend or whatever it might be to get something to eat.

1831
02:39:49,302 --> 02:39:51,704
Whatever it could be, could be worked out administratively.

1832
02:39:52,567 --> 02:39:53,988
That was denied by the mayor.

1833
02:39:54,268 --> 02:39:57,429
Sorry, insufficient funds for the poll workers.

1834
02:39:59,470 --> 02:40:04,452
You know, the school budget, and I'm glad to see the superintendent's still here.

1835
02:40:06,013 --> 02:40:08,734
Several weeks back, I got a unanimous vote from this council.

1836
02:40:09,194 --> 02:40:15,356
I brought up the issue that right now the school department and the city side do not pay for water and sewer.

1837
02:40:16,737 --> 02:40:18,878
In my opinion, water and sewer is a utility.

1838
02:40:19,898 --> 02:40:21,539
It's like gas, it's like electric,

1839
02:40:22,472 --> 02:40:23,853
It's an operating expense.

1840
02:40:24,454 --> 02:40:31,800
You can't run a high school in the boilers, in the bathrooms, and everything else, the pool, associated with the high school, without water and sewer.

1841
02:40:32,260 --> 02:40:33,661
It's an operating expense.

1842
02:40:34,322 --> 02:40:38,245
Some years back, the powers to be took it out of the budget.

1843
02:40:38,725 --> 02:40:39,606
And they said, you know what?

1844
02:40:40,206 --> 02:40:42,088
We're not going to include it in our budget anymore.

1845
02:40:42,908 --> 02:40:45,611
We're going to put it under unaccounted for water.

1846
02:40:46,445 --> 02:40:55,829
And what that is, every rate payer who already pays their bill is going to pay a little additional more to pay for what we call unaccounted for water.

1847
02:40:56,449 --> 02:41:02,071
The only problem with that is the water on the school side and on the city side is accounted for.

1848
02:41:02,831 --> 02:41:03,372
It's meted.

1849
02:41:04,312 --> 02:41:09,034
It's about $400,000 combined from the city and the school side.

1850
02:41:10,152 --> 02:41:14,513
And in my opinion, that should be a budget line item under the operating expenses.

1851
02:41:15,013 --> 02:41:18,054
And it shouldn't fall on the backs of the rate payers.

1852
02:41:18,834 --> 02:41:21,335
It should not fall on the backs of the rate payers.

1853
02:41:21,615 --> 02:41:28,316
That's a way of taking money out of the budget, putting in other things in the budget that you feel are more of a priority.

1854
02:41:29,136 --> 02:41:33,438
It might be a new PR person at 90-something thousand dollars.

1855
02:41:33,878 --> 02:41:35,218
It might be whatever it might be.

1856
02:41:36,358 --> 02:41:38,280
That's a way of shifting money around.

1857
02:41:38,860 --> 02:41:43,405
And in my opinion, if we want a true budget, that should be within this.

1858
02:41:43,685 --> 02:41:49,590
And that was a unanimous vote in this council, and it went to the mayor, and it did not find its way in this budget.

1859
02:41:50,011 --> 02:41:59,700
Another thing that the mayor failed to act upon in this budget, or even come back and give a reasonable response why it couldn't be done.

1860
02:42:05,845 --> 02:42:09,647
On the school budget again, we heard about security.

1861
02:42:10,247 --> 02:42:12,188
Security went up 37%.

1862
02:42:12,809 --> 02:42:15,630
People at home are saying, wow, we are secure.

1863
02:42:16,571 --> 02:42:18,952
Security in the school department went up 37%.

1864
02:42:20,893 --> 02:42:29,818
So I asked the superintendent of schools, I said, Mr. Superintendent, you hired building monitors in addition to the one security guard we have.

1865
02:42:31,323 --> 02:42:36,626
I said, what happens at 3.30 when the school lets out?

1866
02:42:37,406 --> 02:42:41,228
Is there any building monitors or security guards present at 3.30?

1867
02:42:43,009 --> 02:42:44,530
He said, there is not a one.

1868
02:42:45,350 --> 02:42:53,254
However, we do rely on custodians, administrators that still may be around the building to keep an eye out.

1869
02:42:55,295 --> 02:42:59,437
So here we have a building that's open, unsecure, in my opinion,

1870
02:43:00,467 --> 02:43:03,008
and open to the public after school lets out.

1871
02:43:03,948 --> 02:43:08,670
That would be like saying any state building, go up to the state house and say, oh, they're out of session now.

1872
02:43:09,070 --> 02:43:10,050
All security leave.

1873
02:43:10,911 --> 02:43:11,871
There's no reps up here.

1874
02:43:12,011 --> 02:43:12,871
Everyone can leave now.

1875
02:43:14,192 --> 02:43:14,912
That's unheard of.

1876
02:43:15,872 --> 02:43:17,353
That building should be secured.

1877
02:43:17,593 --> 02:43:23,255
There should only be a few entrances that people can get in, and those entrances should be manned.

1878
02:43:24,763 --> 02:43:30,227
And then when the building's locked down, there should still be a security person walking around a building that size.

1879
02:43:32,468 --> 02:43:35,190
You know, a high school, a school, those are soft targets.

1880
02:43:36,331 --> 02:43:38,832
And unfortunately in this city, they're even softer.

1881
02:43:40,053 --> 02:43:44,856
You know, if we hired new building monitors, why put them on all the same time?

1882
02:43:46,617 --> 02:43:48,098
Okay, come in at eight, leave at three.

1883
02:43:49,359 --> 02:43:50,740
Why not stagger the times?

1884
02:43:52,461 --> 02:43:53,742
It makes no sense.

1885
02:43:54,554 --> 02:43:55,495
It makes no sense.

1886
02:43:58,878 --> 02:44:11,731
You know, if something were to happen in our schools and we were to sit back and say, you know what, we were all aware that these buildings are not secured after hours, but they're open, but they're not secured.

1887
02:44:13,312 --> 02:44:18,077
We would feel awful as a council and I'm sure the school committee would feel the same way.

1888
02:44:19,911 --> 02:44:28,336
But just because an incident went by, we had the bomb scares and so forth, and now it's out of sight, out of mind, we can't say, you know what, oh, we're fine, we're fine.

1889
02:44:28,817 --> 02:44:30,118
The threat is still there.

1890
02:44:31,538 --> 02:44:32,799
However, the security's not.

1891
02:44:33,720 --> 02:44:41,505
And I'm not happy with the answers I received from the superintendent of schools regarding the lack of security and the lack of secured buildings, in my opinion.

1892
02:44:41,865 --> 02:44:47,909
I believe our buildings are overused currently right now, and I believe that should be looked at in addition.

1893
02:44:52,978 --> 02:45:02,825
For the past three years, this council asked, when we get a budget, that if we could have an expenditure line item in the current fiscal year.

1894
02:45:03,465 --> 02:45:12,591
So they show FY15, they show FY16, then you would have either an actual, like Councilor Felkel mentioned, or an expenditure to date.

1895
02:45:13,312 --> 02:45:14,552
And then the budget, FY17.

1896
02:45:15,613 --> 02:45:16,954
We've asked for three years.

1897
02:45:17,374 --> 02:45:21,217
We were told by the former budget director, Louise Miller, that's doable.

1898
02:45:21,528 --> 02:45:23,829
and it would have been done in this budget process.

1899
02:45:24,870 --> 02:45:26,110
I asked right at the beginning.

1900
02:45:26,871 --> 02:45:29,892
I wasn't trying to throw any, you know, hold anything off.

1901
02:45:30,172 --> 02:45:32,913
I asked right at the beginning if that could be included.

1902
02:45:33,554 --> 02:45:42,758
It's important to know when an account, coming from someone that does finance, when an account has a surplus or a deficit when you're setting a new budget.

1903
02:45:43,578 --> 02:45:43,799
That's 101.

1904
02:45:45,319 --> 02:45:46,200
It's important to know.

1905
02:45:47,113 --> 02:45:54,378
and to sit back and not have that information, and then at the end of the year, receive a million dollars for transfers.

1906
02:45:54,398 --> 02:45:58,361
243,000 out of fire salaries.

1907
02:45:59,602 --> 02:46:00,342
Guess what that was?

1908
02:46:01,523 --> 02:46:02,704
We didn't hire firefighters.

1909
02:46:03,784 --> 02:46:05,085
But that money will be transferred.

1910
02:46:06,326 --> 02:46:07,827
We told you we were gonna hire firefighters.

1911
02:46:08,327 --> 02:46:09,488
It sounded good last year.

1912
02:46:10,609 --> 02:46:11,890
We all put it as a highlight.

1913
02:46:12,250 --> 02:46:14,752
I'm sure the administration said, look at this highlight.

1914
02:46:16,615 --> 02:46:17,216
But guess what?

1915
02:46:17,536 --> 02:46:18,356
It wasn't funded.

1916
02:46:18,637 --> 02:46:26,603
That money will be used for another appropriation, maybe to fund one of the mayor's other priorities that was underfunded.

1917
02:46:26,944 --> 02:46:27,344
Who knows?

1918
02:46:28,085 --> 02:46:31,948
But these are the games that go on year after year after year.

1919
02:46:32,428 --> 02:46:36,151
And without a proper accounting in the budget, it's going to continue.

1920
02:46:36,932 --> 02:46:39,174
Ann Baker did provide a list here.

1921
02:46:40,375 --> 02:46:44,118
And Ann, if I had two years of time, I could probably match this up.

1922
02:46:44,870 --> 02:46:47,791
with the budget line items, and I probably could do it.

1923
02:46:47,811 --> 02:46:50,212
It would take me some time, but I probably could do it.

1924
02:46:50,652 --> 02:47:00,274
However, the fiscal year ends Friday, and another broken promise by this administration.

1925
02:47:01,935 --> 02:47:12,898
You know, I read an article, I don't know, a couple of months ago in the transcript, the mayor's first 100 days, and it said, priority one, enhancing communication.

1926
02:47:15,495 --> 02:47:20,496
So I guess not sending a representative to our budget meetings is enhancing communication.

1927
02:47:21,576 --> 02:47:27,057
I guess not getting responses that this council has requested is enhancing communication.

1928
02:47:28,417 --> 02:47:45,140
I guess sending the finance person tonight, who by the way is going to be retiring in four weeks and congratulations, I wish you well in, you've done a lot of good for this community, as the budget person, I think does a disservice to not only this council, but to the community.

1929
02:47:47,760 --> 02:47:52,023
And the mayor should have presented the budget, $162 million.

1930
02:47:52,264 --> 02:47:53,405
This is her first budget.

1931
02:47:53,985 --> 02:48:00,110
And as Councilwoman Lungo said, she spent three minutes with this council in the 20 hours we spent going over budget.

1932
02:48:00,911 --> 02:48:02,632
Shame on Mayor Burke.

1933
02:48:03,273 --> 02:48:03,833
Shame on her.

1934
02:48:06,115 --> 02:48:10,398
You know, Mr. President, there are a lot of positive things in this budget.

1935
02:48:13,161 --> 02:48:15,883
But as was stated by Dr. Streller and some of the other speakers,

1936
02:48:16,549 --> 02:48:21,010
We can't go through the same thing over and over again and expect a different outcome.

1937
02:48:21,770 --> 02:48:23,250
It's the definition of insanity.

1938
02:48:26,231 --> 02:48:37,033
And guess what, Mr. President, for those of us that ask questions, that paid attention, that care about the taxpayers' money in this community, it's important to us.

1939
02:48:39,874 --> 02:48:43,895
And I, for one, am not going to put my stamp of approval on this budget.

1940
02:48:46,070 --> 02:48:55,417
If the mayor had the smallest inkling of communication, she would have contacted this council.

1941
02:48:55,717 --> 02:49:00,221
She would have sat down with the council and said, council, you know what, this is a city budget.

1942
02:49:00,481 --> 02:49:02,243
I know it's my budget, I present it.

1943
02:49:02,683 --> 02:49:04,024
What would you like in the budget?

1944
02:49:04,444 --> 02:49:05,945
What do you think is necessary?

1945
02:49:06,366 --> 02:49:10,709
Geez, you've been around for five years, you've been around 14 years, you've been around three years.

1946
02:49:11,310 --> 02:49:12,030
What would you like?

1947
02:49:12,350 --> 02:49:14,232
What do you think is needed in the budget?

1948
02:49:15,438 --> 02:49:16,559
never happened.

1949
02:49:17,380 --> 02:49:18,481
Shame on this mayor.

1950
02:49:19,061 --> 02:49:19,982
Shame on this mayor.

1951
02:49:21,463 --> 02:49:23,545
You know, and my colleagues are welcome to do what they want.

1952
02:49:24,125 --> 02:49:44,042
I know some of my colleagues are new to the budget process, but to go through the same budget process year after year and have no impact at all as a council, and that's my opinion, no impact at all, is a disservice to every taxpayer in this community that expects us to do our job.

1953
02:49:45,427 --> 02:49:48,668
We're a legislative body, and we set the city budget.

1954
02:49:49,829 --> 02:49:51,489
You can count on one hand our function.

1955
02:49:53,490 --> 02:49:54,451
Those are the two top.

1956
02:49:56,351 --> 02:50:02,514
And to let the budget go by, as submitted by the mayor, fine, if that's your intent, fine.

1957
02:50:03,054 --> 02:50:05,655
I, as one member of the council, refuse to do so.

1958
02:50:06,375 --> 02:50:10,837
I'd rather bring the mayor to the table and say, Madam Mayor, why can't we?

1959
02:50:11,297 --> 02:50:12,338
Why can't we do this?

1960
02:50:12,987 --> 02:50:17,170
And if it's the levy limit problem that the mayor has, we reach the levy limit.

1961
02:50:19,131 --> 02:50:22,393
I think that's the first I ever heard, reach the levy limit.

1962
02:50:22,974 --> 02:50:24,775
Gee, McGlynn was here 30 years, I never heard that.

1963
02:50:25,455 --> 02:50:28,737
But under this new mayor, response was we reached the levy limit.

1964
02:50:29,418 --> 02:50:39,865
And my suggestion back to the mayor is, then maybe we should look at the stipends, the confidentiality stipends you give your staff people.

1965
02:50:41,390 --> 02:50:47,837
How many people are hired when you get a job and you walk into the job and they say, okay, here's what you have to do.

1966
02:50:48,658 --> 02:50:51,881
And then they say, on top of that, this is confidential information.

1967
02:50:52,923 --> 02:50:57,367
We're going to pay you over and above your salary because you're dealing with confidential information.

1968
02:50:58,029 --> 02:50:58,810
Doesn't happen.

1969
02:50:59,631 --> 02:51:01,312
Doesn't happen in the private sector.

1970
02:51:01,913 --> 02:51:02,954
That's party or job.

1971
02:51:03,454 --> 02:51:20,772
So if there are people in the mayor's office that are handling confidential information, and there may be, and there's people in the assessor's office, and the people in the treasurer collector's office, and there's people in every department that are handling confidential information that aren't getting these stipends, they happen to be to just a few in the mayor's office.

1972
02:51:21,708 --> 02:51:34,670
Maybe we could cut that portion out of the budget, and maybe we can add something for the arts, or maybe we can add something that we think would be a bigger bang for our buck, rather than padding someone's salary.

1973
02:51:34,690 --> 02:51:35,810
Because that's all it is.

1974
02:51:36,270 --> 02:51:37,071
Don't fool yourself.

1975
02:51:37,591 --> 02:51:38,431
That's all it is.

1976
02:51:38,771 --> 02:51:40,771
It's a padding of someone's salary.

1977
02:51:42,812 --> 02:51:47,532
So, Mr. President, with that being said, I will not support the budget here tonight.

1978
02:51:48,633 --> 02:51:50,913
I refuse to support it on the basis that

1979
02:51:51,250 --> 02:51:55,513
The mayor refused to send anyone that can answer questions to our budget meeting.

1980
02:51:56,294 --> 02:52:00,818
She made this budget, in my opinion, the worst budget process I've ever been through.

1981
02:52:01,678 --> 02:52:04,140
She didn't look for any input from this council.

1982
02:52:04,721 --> 02:52:06,682
She didn't look for any input from the community.

1983
02:52:07,123 --> 02:52:14,909
She failed to put the budget or proposed budget on the city websites for open transparency and open government.

1984
02:52:16,579 --> 02:52:17,799
Who cares after the fact?

1985
02:52:18,419 --> 02:52:23,940
Mr. President, if you ran your funeral home like the mayor's run in this city, you'd be out of business right now.

1986
02:52:25,721 --> 02:52:28,501
You shouldn't settle for any less because it's the city budget.

1987
02:52:29,221 --> 02:52:32,202
You should hold it to the same standard, Mr. President, as you do for your funeral home.

1988
02:52:32,262 --> 02:52:33,222
Over 30 minutes, consulate.

1989
02:52:33,242 --> 02:52:34,202
Thank you very much.

1990
02:52:34,222 --> 02:52:35,122
I'm not done yet, Mr. President.

1991
02:52:35,182 --> 02:52:35,682
You are.

1992
02:52:35,702 --> 02:52:37,563
The chair awaits a motion.

1993
02:52:38,343 --> 02:52:39,703
Mr. President, I am not done yet.

1994
02:52:39,723 --> 02:52:41,343
You didn't tell me what time I had.

1995
02:52:41,363 --> 02:52:42,064
I am not done yet.

1996
02:52:43,484 --> 02:52:44,204
I still have comments.

1997
02:52:49,373 --> 02:52:50,494
Is there a motion on the floor?

1998
02:52:50,534 --> 02:52:56,838
I'd like to hear from the superintendent of school, Mr. President, who is here regarding the security.

1999
02:52:56,858 --> 02:53:09,147
I'd like to hear his comments regarding why buildings aren't secure after school lights up.

2000
02:53:09,167 --> 02:53:16,753
Mr. President, members of the council, I understand that Councilor Marks has legitimate concerns about security.

2001
02:53:17,504 --> 02:53:25,466
and the like, but I want to offer a few thoughts, and hopefully, you know, maybe it'll help us understand each other, okay?

2002
02:53:26,387 --> 02:53:27,807
Well, let's see what happens.

2003
02:53:28,527 --> 02:53:29,208
Let's see what happens.

2004
02:53:30,308 --> 02:53:34,169
You know, during the day, we have intensive security.

2005
02:53:34,329 --> 02:53:37,530
It's not perfect, but it's a lot better than most school systems.

2006
02:53:38,651 --> 02:53:46,473
We have, and we, and you know, some of the events that happened this year obviously ramped up some of the things that we did, because people felt a need to do that.

2007
02:53:46,962 --> 02:53:56,209
when the majority of youngsters are there in the school, and they're in concentrated areas, and they need that kind of coverage.

2008
02:53:57,190 --> 02:53:59,332
So we have a lot going on.

2009
02:53:59,372 --> 02:54:00,053
We have cameras.

2010
02:54:00,093 --> 02:54:00,813
We have monitors.

2011
02:54:00,833 --> 02:54:01,434
We have guards.

2012
02:54:01,994 --> 02:54:03,635
We have resource officers.

2013
02:54:03,675 --> 02:54:05,117
We have door locks in the systems.

2014
02:54:05,617 --> 02:54:08,039
You know, we have ID systems now.

2015
02:54:08,960 --> 02:54:16,626
We meet with CBJ every week to determine what's happening in the streets, so when it comes in Monday morning, we know what's going on, what happened over the weekend,

2016
02:54:17,671 --> 02:54:20,373
We have constant contact with the police.

2017
02:54:20,393 --> 02:54:23,575
We have constant contact with the DA's office, the courts.

2018
02:54:24,255 --> 02:54:27,537
There's a lot going on that people don't see.

2019
02:54:28,258 --> 02:54:32,521
We belong to NMLEC, which is a regional group that brings things in.

2020
02:54:33,461 --> 02:54:40,526
But council raises the issue of what happens around 3.30 when things are over for the main part of the day.

2021
02:54:42,810 --> 02:54:47,773
Maybe, just maybe, it would be nice to have all kinds of people there, but you've got to ask a couple questions.

2022
02:54:48,693 --> 02:54:50,434
How functionally effective would it be?

2023
02:54:51,314 --> 02:54:54,256
Not just cosmetic, how functionally effective would it be?

2024
02:54:54,936 --> 02:54:59,379
I'm standing here right now, and there are probably a few people in this room who don't like me.

2025
02:54:59,439 --> 02:55:03,721
I don't know if that's true, but I have the feeling that there's some people who don't really like me.

2026
02:55:04,161 --> 02:55:05,282
My back is to the wall.

2027
02:55:05,682 --> 02:55:07,923
There's no police officer guarding this council.

2028
02:55:08,701 --> 02:55:11,623
There's no police officer at churches and synagogues.

2029
02:55:11,963 --> 02:55:16,706
There's no police officer at the restaurants we go to, in the parks where the Little Leagues play.

2030
02:55:19,087 --> 02:55:20,608
Point of information, Mr. President.

2031
02:55:20,648 --> 02:55:21,268
Well, I don't know.

2032
02:55:21,328 --> 02:55:22,429
I'm trying to give a point of information.

2033
02:55:22,449 --> 02:55:23,450
You're trying to give an answer.

2034
02:55:23,470 --> 02:55:25,591
You're great at circumlocution, Mr. Superintendent.

2035
02:55:25,631 --> 02:55:27,032
No, I'm trying to give you an answer.

2036
02:55:27,072 --> 02:55:27,872
I'm trying to point out to you.

2037
02:55:27,912 --> 02:55:31,654
First of all, I didn't ask for a point of information, please.

2038
02:55:31,855 --> 02:55:32,915
If you'll let me speak, I will.

2039
02:55:33,896 --> 02:55:35,237
I didn't ask for a police officer.

2040
02:55:35,377 --> 02:55:37,118
So that is your first error.

2041
02:55:38,052 --> 02:55:47,335
I asked specifically about after hours, Mr. Superintendent, and you have no security and you have no secure building after hours.

2042
02:55:47,375 --> 02:55:54,158
If you can address that, rather than going into these things about having police officers at every door, that is not what we stated.

2043
02:55:54,958 --> 02:55:56,159
I'm trying to.

2044
02:55:56,639 --> 02:56:05,342
Churches are one thing, Mr. President, but a school that houses thousands of our students deserves the right for security and the right to have a secured building.

2045
02:56:05,742 --> 02:56:07,763
Not in the afternoon, not thousands in the building.

2046
02:56:08,438 --> 02:56:11,740
You know, the parks where the kids play their sports.

2047
02:56:12,240 --> 02:56:14,301
I don't see all kinds of people there.

2048
02:56:15,001 --> 02:56:21,244
Obviously, it would be nice to have all kinds of people around who are doing that officially.

2049
02:56:22,425 --> 02:56:25,086
But you talk about all the things that we want in these budgets.

2050
02:56:25,146 --> 02:56:29,308
You talk about all the things that we would like to do and all the repairs we'd like to make.

2051
02:56:30,208 --> 02:56:35,931
And I personally think that putting people in these roles is not giving us functional value.

2052
02:56:36,391 --> 02:56:38,032
I think we can get the same return

2053
02:56:38,617 --> 02:56:46,242
from people who are crime watchers, if you will, people who can pick up their phone or use their cell and call 911 if necessary.

2054
02:56:46,602 --> 02:56:49,244
I don't think you need that kind of coverage.

2055
02:56:49,865 --> 02:56:51,646
So we've talked about it.

2056
02:56:52,306 --> 02:56:53,167
I'm listening to you.

2057
02:56:53,367 --> 02:56:54,008
I hear you.

2058
02:56:54,408 --> 02:57:00,112
Maybe there's something we can think about, but I don't think it's the kind of thing that we could do

2059
02:57:01,331 --> 02:57:03,913
with fidelity around the schools in the afternoons.

2060
02:57:04,293 --> 02:57:11,479
And I don't think that it's different than what we expect from our little leagues, from our youth programs, soccer programs.

2061
02:57:11,659 --> 02:57:12,500
They're all over the city.

2062
02:57:13,781 --> 02:57:16,163
Random acts of violence happen anywhere.

2063
02:57:17,624 --> 02:57:27,672
So to think that the schools are more likely to have them in the afternoon than the parks where the kids play, or the churches where people go to, or the restaurants where people eat.

2064
02:57:29,192 --> 02:57:30,192
I don't think that's real.

2065
02:57:30,912 --> 02:57:32,133
And so, it's an exchange.

2066
02:57:32,733 --> 02:57:33,953
But, you know, I'll think about it.

2067
02:57:34,013 --> 02:57:35,433
Maybe there's some things we can do.

2068
02:57:35,854 --> 02:57:42,115
But I don't think it's a just refusal to consider the issue.

2069
02:57:42,695 --> 02:57:44,596
I think it's well thought through at this point in time.

2070
02:57:44,616 --> 02:57:45,996
But maybe you don't agree with me.

2071
02:57:46,316 --> 02:57:48,176
That's what I think is really the issue.

2072
02:57:48,216 --> 02:57:49,517
We just don't agree on the subject.

2073
02:57:50,817 --> 02:57:51,077
Mr. President.

2074
02:57:53,278 --> 02:57:54,858
Councillor Marks.

2075
02:57:55,878 --> 02:57:58,719
You know, I realize within a budget you have to make decisions.

2076
02:57:59,577 --> 02:58:04,240
But security is a decision that I'm not willing to let go.

2077
02:58:05,541 --> 02:58:09,123
Security is just as important as the teacher in the classroom.

2078
02:58:12,405 --> 02:58:27,515
And in my opinion, Mr. President, to say during the day, when the students are in there, that you have to check in, you have to show an ID, you have to sign in, you have to — and that process has been tightened up — you're right — recently, Mr. Superintendent.

2079
02:58:28,318 --> 02:58:36,812
